Llm kv store technical details, smallest llm




Good question. The KV store (key–value cache) is one of the most important technical pieces for LLM performance, especially on small hardware like phones or 16 GB GPUs. I will break it down from the lowest level.

⸻

1. What the LLM KV Store Actually Is

In transformer models, every token produces attention keys and values that later tokens reference.

During generation the model stores:
	•	K = key vectors
	•	V = value vectors

for every token in the context.

These are saved in the KV cache so the model does not recompute earlier tokens.

Without a KV cache:

token 1 -> recompute
token 2 -> recompute tokens 1–2
token 3 -> recompute tokens 1–3

With KV cache:

token 1 -> store KV
token 2 -> read KV(1)
token 3 -> read KV(1,2)

That turns generation from O(n²) compute to roughly O(n).

⸻

2. KV Cache Structure

For each transformer layer the model stores:

layer
   K[tokens][attention_dim]
   V[tokens][attention_dim]

So memory grows with:

tokens × layers × hidden_size


⸻

3. KV Memory Formula

Approximate formula:

KV_memory ≈ tokens × layers × hidden_dim × 2 × bytes_per_value

Explanation:
	•	tokens = context length
	•	layers = transformer depth
	•	hidden_dim = attention size
	•	×2 = key + value

⸻

Example: 7B Model

Typical config:

layers: 32
hidden_dim: 4096

For 8k context:

8000 × 32 × 4096 × 2 × 2 bytes
≈ ~4 GB

This is why large contexts explode VRAM usage.

⸻

4. KV Cache Compression

Newer systems reduce KV size with:

1. quantized KV

store keys/values as
	•	fp16 → int8
	•	fp16 → int4

Reduces memory ~2–4×.

⸻

2. sliding window attention

Only keep recent tokens.

Example:

context window: 32k
active KV: last 4k

Used by many long-context models.

⸻

3. grouped-query attention (GQA)

Instead of every head having its own KV:

many heads -> shared KV

Reduces memory significantly.

Used in:
	•	Llama 3
	•	Qwen2

⸻

5. Smallest Possible LLM

For a real language model, the practical lower bound is about:

300M – 1B parameters

Examples:

extremely small
	•	SmolLM (~135M)

Memory:

~300 MB quantized

But reasoning is limited.

